ica -- t21. Older Heads on Younger Bodies -- t22. Confections, Concoctions, and Conceptions -- t23. Living in a World of Words -- t24. The Tidy House -- tPART IV: Sourcebook -- tSection A: Introduction -- t25. Reaching Juvenile Markets -- t26. Does Your ''Research'' Embrace the Boy of Today? -- t27. ''Selling'' Food to Children -- tSection B. The Family in Crisis -- t28. After the Family-What? -- t29. Against the Threat of Mother Love -- tSection C: Children at War -- t30. Children in Wartime: Parents' Questions -- t31. You Are Citizen Soldiers -- t32. Raise Your Boy to Be a Soldier -- tSection D: Popular Culture and the Family -- t33. ''Such Trivia As Comic Books'' -- t34. The Play's the Thing -- tSection E: Freedom and Responsibility -- t35. New Parents for Old -- t36. Families and the World Outside -- t37. Time Bombs in Our Homes -- t38. Democratic and Autocratic Child Rearing -- tSection F: The Permissive Family -- t39. The Contemporary Mother and Father -- t40. The New Oedipal Drama of the Permissive Family -- t41. The Modern Pediocracy -- tContributors -- tPermissions -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEvery major political and social dispute of the twentieth century has been fought on the backs of our children, from the economic reforms of the progressive era through the social readjustments of civil rights era and on to the current explosion of anxieties about everything from the national debt to the digital revolution. Far from noncombatants whom we seek to protect from the contamination posed by adult knowledge, children form the very basis on which we fight over the nature and values of our society, and over our hopes and fears for the future. Unfortunately, our understanding of childhood and children has not kept pace with their crucial and rapidly changing roles in our culture. Pulling together a range of different thinkers who have rethought the myths of childhood innocence, The Children's Culture Reader develops a profile of children as creative and critical thinkers who shape society even as it shapes them. Representing a range of thinking from history, psychology, anthropology, sociology, economics, women's studies, literature, and media studies, The Children's Culture Reader focuses on issues of parent-child relations, child labor, education, play, and especially the relationship of children to mass media and consumer culture. The contributors include Martha Wolfenstein, Philippe Aries, Jacqueline Rose, James Kincaid, Lynn Spigel, Valerie Walkerdine, Ellen Seiter, Annette Kuhn, Eve Sedgwick, Henry Giroux, and Nancy Scheper-Hughes. Including a groundbreaking introduction by the editor and a sourcebook section which excerpts a range of material from popular magazines to child rearing guides from the past 75 years, The Children's Culture Reader will propel our understanding of children and childhood into the next century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 0aChildren in popular culturezUnited States. 0aChildren in popular culture. 0aChildrenxSocial conditions. 0aChildrenzUnited StatesxSocial conditions. 0aMass media and childrenzUnited States. 0aMass media and children. 0aPopular culturezUnited States. 0aPopular culture. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Children's Studies.2bisacsh1 aJenkins, Henry, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814743782423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780814743782.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK